  "text": "SHMT2 is known to play a vital role in one-carbon metabolism and functions as a binding protein influencing the degradation of other proteins [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Thus, we not only investigated the metabolic regulation of SHMT2 but also analyzed its binding proteins using LC-MS/MS analysis (Fig 1A) . The results showed that p53 was one of the SHMT2 binding proteins, while KIAA0157, a known binding protein, was also identified (Fig 1B) . HCT116 cells that contained wild-type p53 but not mutant p53 were used to verify the binding of p53 and SHMT2. Coimmunoprecipitation experiments with transiently transfected SHMT2 showed that SHMT2 coprecipitated with p53 ( Fig 1C) . Endogenous p53-SHMT2 binding was also detectable in HCT116 cells (Fig 1D) .",
